The '''Babel Proclamation''' was issued by [[Iowa]]'s [[List of Governors of Iowa|Governor]] [[William L. Harding]] on May 14, 1918. Harding took the [[Anti-German sentiment]] in the wake of [[World War I]] further than any other state.
According to this proclamation, "only [[English language|English]] was legal in public or private schools, in public conversations, on trains, over the telephone, at all meetings, and in all religious services."<ref>Derr, Nancy. "The Babel Proclamation," ''The Palimpsest'' 60, No. 4 (July/August 1979): 100-101.</ref>
==Bibliography== *Frese, Stephen J. "[http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ht/39.1/frese.html Divided by a Common Language: The Babel Proclamation and its Influence in Iowa History]," ''The History Teacher'' November 2005 (13 August 2007).
