==Documentation==
Sources for documentation of Nduke language have been noted by Palmer 2005.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Palmer|first1=Bill|title=New Georgia|url=http://www.surrey.ac.uk/lcts/bill.palmer/NWS_site/Bibliography/New_Georgia.htm|website=An annotated bibliography of Northwest Solomonic materials|publisher=University of Surrey|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> Grammar notes above have been sourced from Scales 1997.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Scales|first1=Ian|title=Indexing in Nduke (Solomon Islands) (Seminar paper)|date=1998|publisher=Department of Linguistics, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, Australian National University|location=Canberra}}</ref> Wordlists include Hocart 1908,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hocart|first1=Arthur M.|title=Nduke vocabulary (TS)|date=1908|publisher=TS held at Turnbull Library, Auckland}}</ref> Tryon and Hackman 1983,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tryon|first1=Darrell T.|last2=Hackman|first2=Bryan D.|title=Solomon Islands languages: an internal classification|date=1983|publisher=Pacific Linguistics|location=Canberra}}</ref> and an online wordlist based on Tryon and Hackman.<ref>{{cite web|title=Language: Nduke|url=http://language.psy.auckland.ac.nz/austronesian/language.php?id=521|website=Austronesian Basic Vocabulary Database|publisher=University of Auckland}}</ref> Lexical and Bible translation work are currently underway.
