[[Image:Dick Libby.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Quartermaster Dick Libby, USN, an Old Salt: "Twenty years in the Navy. "Never drunk on duty - never sober on liberty." <ref> http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/images/kn00001/kn00582l.htm </ref> Portrait painted circa 1834 by [[Charles O. Cole]] ]]
An "'''old salt'''" is an old sailor who is often a raconteur, or teller of [[nautical fiction|sea stories]]. Much of the [[history]] and traditions of mariners are passed from generation to generation by these sea stories as told and retold by old salts. Sea stories may be [[truth]]ful, half-truths, or falsehoods. However, they always enhance the reputations of sailors.

In the [[United States Navy]], the "Old Salt" is a title passed to the longest-serving [[Surface Warfare Officer]] on active duty.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rafael|first1=Martie|title=Navy Passes "Old Salt" Award|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=64457|accessdate=16 April 2018|agency=U.S. Navy}}</ref> The award, currently held by Admiral [[Kurt W. Tidd]], Commander, [[U.S. Southern Command]], honors the officer with the earliest standing SWO qualification.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Tyrell|title=Vice Adm. Tidd Receives Surface Navy Association's "Old Salt" Award|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=87798|accessdate=16 April 2018|agency=U.S. Navy}}</ref>

